      <div class="hero">
        <div>
          <span class="eyebrow">Route planner</span>
          <h1>First setup routes</h1>
          <p class="lede">If you do not want to read everything first, start here. Pick the route that sounds most like your actual life, then follow the smallest set of links that gets you moving without drowning in docks, ropes, and seagull noise.</p>
        </div>
        <aside class="note-card">
          <h3>General rule</h3>
          <p>Start with one boring, useful workflow. The people who enjoy these systems most are usually the ones who begin with a single real job instead of a fantasy of total life automation.</p>
        </aside>
      </div>

      <div class="grid">
        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">Route 1</span>
          <h2>I want the main official path</h2>
          <ol>
            <li>Read <a href="https://openclaw.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OpenClaw</a>.</li>
            <li>Keep <a href="https://docs.openclaw.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the docs</a> open while you install.</li>
            <li>Use the GitHub repo when you need implementation detail.</li>
          </ol>
          <p><strong>Best for:</strong> people who want the canonical coastline.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">Route 2</span>
          <h2>I want something smaller and clearer</h2>
          <ol>
            <li>Start with <a href="https://nanoclaw.dev/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NanoClaw</a>.</li>
            <li>Read the repo and Discussions before overcomplicating the setup.</li>
            <li>Keep the first use case narrow and local.</li>
          </ol>
          <p><strong>Best for:</strong> cautious tinkerers and people who value legibility.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">Route 3</span>
          <h2>I want tiny hardware and low overhead</h2>
          <ol>
            <li>Go to <a href="https://picoclaw.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PicoClaw</a>.</li>
            <li>Read the repo with hardware constraints in mind.</li>
            <li>Choose one compact workflow and prove it on modest hardware.</li>
          </ol>
          <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Pi projects, edge experiments, and resource discipline.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">Route 4</span>
          <h2>I mainly care about stronger rails</h2>
          <ol>
            <li>Start with <a href="https://docs.nvidia.com/nemoclaw/latest/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NemoClaw docs</a>.</li>
            <li>Read the warnings and alpha status before getting attached.</li>
            <li>Treat it as a security-forward experiment, not a finished domestic appliance.</li>
          </ol>
          <p><strong>Best for:</strong> people asking safety questions first.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="card full">
          <span class="mini">First useful jobs</span>
          <h2>Good beginner workflows</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>daily reminders that actually matter</li>
            <li>message routing and triage</li>
            <li>local code assistance</li>
            <li>a narrow self-hosted helper for one recurring problem</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Start here, then add complexity only when the first little harbor is already serving you well.</p>
        </section>
      </div>

